#. type: Plain text
#: origin/smbfs.txt:8
msgid "SYNOPSIS: How to create a LFS installation if you haven't got a lot of space"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/smbfs.txt:13
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"DESCRIPTION:\n"
"  This hint describes a way to create an (nA)LFS system if you don't have "
"any space\n"
"  on your LFS system. For this hint you do need a second (possibly windows) "
"\n"
"  computer with enough space for the compilation.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/smbfs.txt:15
msgid "ATTACHMENTS:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/smbfs.txt:17
msgid "None"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/smbfs.txt:20
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"PREREQUISITES:\n"
"  - This hint requires that you have sufficient knowledge of "
"LinuxFromScratch.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '  - '
#: origin/smbfs.txt:23
msgid ""
"This hint requires that you have a second windows (preferably XP) PC and a "
"network connection between the 2 computers."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '  - '
#: origin/smbfs.txt:26
msgid ""
"This hint assumes you use the LFS LiveCD but any host system with smbfs / "
"smbmount will do fine"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/smbfs.txt:31
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"HINT:\n"
"                        ---------------------------------\n"
"                       | CONFIGURING YOUR WINDOWS SYSTEM |\n"
"                        ---------------------------------\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/smbfs.txt:36
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"  First thing we have to do is configure your windows system. Since the only "
"\n"
"  windows system i have is a windows XP OS, i can only explain how to do it "
"for\n"
"  Windows XP, if someone has a diffrent windows version feel free to email "
"me\n"
"  the instructions on how to set up a similar situation on that os.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/smbfs.txt:38
#, no-wrap
msgid "  Now lets start:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/smbfs.txt:41
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"  First thing you have to do is find a partition on your computer with "
"atleast \n"
"  6 GB of free space (10 GB is recommended).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/smbfs.txt:48
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"  Create a folder called LFSDATA.\n"
"  Share it by right clicking on the folder and clicking on properties.\n"
"  Select the Sharing tab\n"
"  Make sure that the box next to 'Share this folder on the network' and \n"
"  'allow network users to change my files' are checked in\n"
"  Make sure the share is called LFSDATA\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/smbfs.txt:50
#, no-wrap
msgid "  Your windows system is now setup :-)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/smbfs.txt:54
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"                -----------------------------------------------\n"
"               | CREATE AND MOUNT ALL THE DIFFRENT FILESYSTEMS |\n"
"                -----------------------------------------------\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/smbfs.txt:56
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"  Alright, this is the more difficult part. First lets create the share "
"mount point\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/smbfs.txt:58
#, no-wrap
msgid "\tmkdir /mnt/LFSDATA\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/smbfs.txt:61
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"  Then, mount the share using smbmount:\n"
"\tsmbmount //[YOUR_WINDOWS_XP_IP]/LFSDATA LFSDATA\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/smbfs.txt:66
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"  What we have to do now is create 3 files with an ext2 filesystem. The "
"reason for \n"
"  this is: permissions. Especially when you use nALFS, this can be a real "
"problem\n"
"  if you use a direct windows XP share with a windows XP filesystem. So :-) "
"lets \n"
"  create the files:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/smbfs.txt:70
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\tdd if=/dev/zero of=/mnt/LFSDATA/root    bs=1M count=2045\n"
"\tdd if=/dev/zero of=/mnt/LFSDATA/tools   bs=1M count=2045\n"
"\tdd if=/dev/zero of=/mnt/LFSDATA/sources bs=1M count=2045\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/smbfs.txt:72
#, no-wrap
msgid "  Then, create the filesystems inside those files:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/smbfs.txt:76
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\tmkfs.ext2 /mnt/LFSDATA/root\n"
"\tmkfs.ext2 /mnt/LFSDATA/tools\n"
"\tmkfs.ext2 /mnt/LFSDATA/sources\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/smbfs.txt:78
#, no-wrap
msgid "  With these 3 commands you will get the following error message:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/smbfs.txt:82
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\tmke2fs 1.37 (21-Mar-2005)\n"
"\troot is not a block special device.\n"
"\tProceed anyway? (y,n)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/smbfs.txt:85
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"  press y here :-)\n"
"  The next step is to mount it all:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/smbfs.txt:92
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\tmkdir /mnt/lfs\n"
"\tmount /mnt/LFSDATA/root /mnt/lfs -o loop\n"
"\tmkdir /mnt/lfs/tools\n"
"\tmount /mnt/LFSDATA/tools /mnt/lfs/tools -o loop\n"
"\tmkdir /mnt/lfs/tools/packages-6.1.1 \n"
"        mount /mnt/LFSDATA/sources /mnt/lfs/packages-6.1.1 -o loop\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/smbfs.txt:96
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\t\t                --------------\n"
"\t\t               | USE THE BOOK |\n"
"                \t\t--------------\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/smbfs.txt:99
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"  Well - as the title already says :-) its now time to run the book or the "
"nALFS \n"
"  script and any additions you want. Except do not do the chapter 2, 8 and 9 "
"parts :-)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/smbfs.txt:103
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\t\t                ---------------\n"
"        \t\t       | THE LAST STEP |\n"
"                \t\t---------------\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/smbfs.txt:107
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"  Well - you are almost done :-) the only thing you have to do now is copy "
"all \n"
"  the files you created in the 'root' file to your true partition. It is now "
"time\n"
"  for a slightly modified version of chapter 2 ;-)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/smbfs.txt:111
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"  First you will have to unmount all the unneccesarry bits. This means \n"
"  /tools/packages-6.1.1 and /tools (if you have created any other temperary "
"mounts \n"
"  you have to unmount them aswell)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/smbfs.txt:115
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\tumount /mnt/lfs/tools/packages-6.1.1\n"
"\tumount /mnt/lfs/tools\n"
"        rmdir /mnt/lfs/tools\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/smbfs.txt:118
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"  Then you have to create a partition. I assume you know how to do this and "
"\n"
"  otherwise check chapter 2 of the LFS book.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/smbfs.txt:121
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"  For now i assume your new partition has the device node /dev/hda1. If it "
"does \n"
"  not change the commands where neccesary.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/smbfs.txt:123
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"  Now you will have to create a temporary mountpoint for the host "
"partition:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/smbfs.txt:126
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"\tmkdir /mnt/tmp\n"
"\tmount /dev/hda1 /mnt/tmp\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/smbfs.txt:129
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"  Then, copy the contents of /mnt/lfs to /mnt/tmp:\n"
"\tcp /mnt/lfs/* /mnt/tmp -pr\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/smbfs.txt:134
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"  and unmount the lfs and tmp mounts and remount /dev/hda1 to /mnt/lfs\n"
"        umount /mnt/lfs\n"
"\tumount /mnt/tmp\n"
"\tmount /dev/hda1 /mnt/lfs\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/smbfs.txt:136
#, no-wrap
msgid "  Then it is now time to chroot back into /mnt/lfs and do chapter 8 and 9.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/smbfs.txt:138
#, no-wrap
msgid "  Thats it :-) I hope its of some use to somebody out there :-)\n"
msgstr ""

